# Better Late Than Never: Analyzing Tübingen’s Buses

*Sebastian Böhler, Alexandra Keller, Ella Rumohr*

## Abstract

Many cities, including Tübingen, rely on an efficiently functioning bus network for public transport. By 2025, public opinion was that buses were frequently delayed and suboptimal, which increased frustration among students and clinicians. To test these perceptions, we collected and analyzed bus arrival information provided via the TRIAS public transport interface, operated by the regional transit authority (via the MobiData BW/efa-bw service). We analyzed the delays by bus line, bus stop, time of day and weather conditions. 

## Introduction

In (Linus nach genauerem Datum fragen?\!), students in Tübingen launched a petition to draw politicians' attention to their frustration with the buses in the city. They describe delays and overly crowded buses, putting a strain on students' and clinicians' ability to get to work. Complaints were going as far as saying "I don't go to the lectures anymore, due to the bus situation" (*Bus Statt Frust*, 2025). But are these complaints justified or are they just a typical student excuse? For us, a typical student response is investigating and testing your hypotheses. Thus, we analyse whether the buses are indeed as delayed as subjectively experienced. Looking into the bus delays officially tracked by the city allows us to support or refute subjective perceptions with statistical and graphical analyses. We examine the lines, times of day and stops primarily affected by delays, required for evaluation and improval of the bus schedule.

## Data Collection and Analysis

For our study, we analyzed bus arrival information provided through the TRIAS public transport interface operated by the regional transit authority (via the MobiData BW / efa-bw service). Arrival times are measured via GPS coordinates when buses enter the designated stop area. We implemented a scheduled cloud function that queries the TRIAS API at hourly intervals and retrieves real-time departure information for bus stops within a fixed spatial radius around the city of Tübingen. Each query produced a snapshot of scheduled and estimated arrivals for multiple upcoming departures, allowing us to observe how estimated delays vary across bus lines, locations, and times of day.

For each observed stop event, we record the bus line, destination, stop identifier, scheduled arrival time, and estimated arrival time. From the scheduled and estimated arrival timestamps, we compute a delay variable defined as the difference between the estimated and scheduled arrival time, measured in seconds.

Data was collected continuously over a period from November 11, 2025 to January 30, 2026, spanning approximately 11 weeks. The final dataset covers 366 unique stops and 51 bus lines.

In addition to stop-level data, we retrieved trip-level schedule information describing complete bus journeys. For each journey, the TRIAS API returns the full sequence of stops along the route, including stops the bus has already visited and stops it will visit in the future. To ensure our analysis uses only realized delays rather than predictions, we filter the trip data to include only stops labelled as previously visited.

The filtered trip-level data is stored separately from stop-level departures but was linked via shared journey identifiers. The resulting dataset enables analysis at multiple granularities: individual stop events for aggregate delay statistics, and complete journey sequences for studying delay propagation along routes, for example whether delays accumulate, remain constant, or disperse as a bus progresses through its stops.

In comparison to bus statistics provided by the cities which report only mean delays and percentages (\\citet, \\citep), our research employs a more comprehensive analytical approach by integrating three key dimensions: (a) spatial factors, as delays may be disproportionately related to a few core spots. (Park et al., 2018), (b) temporal influences, including time of day, which reveal when delays are most severe and may allow schedule redesign, and (c) weather conditions. Weather has been underrepresented in delay models, yet, studies demonstrate its value, particularly in combination with time of day, season and location (Chen et al., 2025; Brazil et al., 2017; Mohammadi, 2023). While predictive models for bus arrivals are common for simulating potential delays (see Chen et al., 2025\) ~~and offer valuable forecasting capabilities~~, our focus remains on evaluating the observed delay patterns.

Prior to analysis, we applied several data cleaning steps. The available data did not include negative delay values; a delay of zero represents arrivals that are on time or ahead of schedule, as the system does not explicitly report early arrivals.

Extreme delays exceeding 30 minutes were documented but retained, as they represent real service disruptions (0.85% of records). Using median and quantile statistics mitigates outlier influence while preserving information about service issues. Since our data collection focused on Tübingen, stop coordinates are only available for stops within or close to the city; for network visualizations, we filtered erroneous long-distance edges that arose when routes extended beyond this area. A bus is considered “late” if the delay exceeds 2 minutes, aligning with common transit agency definitions. 

From the cleaned dataset, we investigated how delays are distributed across the network and what proportion of buses are late. We examined whether delays vary systematically by time of day, day of week, or weather conditions. We also assessed whether the schedule change on December 14, 2025 had a measurable effect on delays, independent of the holiday period, and whether delays accumulate along routes as buses progress through their stops.

Figure 1: Exploratory analysis of Tübingen bus delays. (A) Distribution of departure delays showing a right-skewed pattern. (B) Mean delay by hour of day with 95% confidence intervals. ©  Top 10 busiest stops by departure count. (D) Mean delay by weather condition with sample sizes. Overview of key descriptive patterns:  (A); (B); (C); (D)

The distribution of delays is right-skewed, with a spike near zero and a one-sided tail toward late departures, as early arrivals are not recorded in the data (Figure 1A). Of all departures, 65.4% are late (delay \> 0 min); among these, the median delay is 1.50 minutes and the mean is 3.41 minutes. Using a 2-minute threshold, 25.8% of departures are late, with a media delay of 4.10 minutes among this group. Temporal aggregation by hour of day reveals clear patterns, with elevated delays during afternoon hours (peaking around 15-16h) and notably high delays during late night hours (0-2h), though the latter are based on fewer observations (Figure 1B). Spatial analysis shows that a small number of central stops, particularly Tübingen Hauptbahnhof (6,436 departures), account for a disproportionately large share of observations (Figure 1C). 

*Weather*

Dry conditions dominate the dataset (88.7%, n=124,461), followed by rain (7.3%, n=10,307) and snow (2.2%, n=3,075). Snow shows the highest mean delay at 7.50 minutes with a 90th percentile of 25.9 minutes, substantially higher than dry conditions (mean 2.14 min, p90 5.1 min). Rain shows similar delays to dry conditions (mean 2.21 min). Fog, hail, and sleet each account for less than 1% of observations and lower mean delays (1.0-1.7 min). Given the small sample sizes for adverse weather, these differences should be interpreted cautiously (Figure 1D). Contextual analysis by weather condition shows that dry conditions dominate the dataset, while adverse weather phenomena such as snow or sleet occur relatively infrequently. Interestingly, mean delays under adverse weather conditions, such as snow, are not higher than under dry conditions. Confidence intervals and sample sizes are reported to ensure that differences are interpreted cautiously. (D)

*Temporal Patterns*

Time-of-day analysis reveals clear patterns (Figure 1B). The afternoon peak (hour 16), shows an average delay of 4.46 minutes, with the 90th percentile reaching 12.6 minutes. Late night hours (0-3h) show the highest delays, with hour 2 averaging 7.52 minutes, though based on substantially fewer observations (600-1000 per hours vs 8,000 \- 10,000 during daytime). 

Morning rush hour (6-9h) average 1.22-2.44 minutes. Midday periods (10-15h) show moderate delays of 1.2-2.3 minutes. Early morning hours (4-5h) show the lowest delays at under 1 minute. Weekend and weekdays are similar (mean 2.20 vs 2.24 minutes).

Analysis of trip data shows a positive correlation between stop position along a route and delay magnitude (r \= 0.16). Mean delay increases from 1.44 minutes at the first stop to approximately 2.5-3.2 minutes by stop 12-15, indicating that delays accumulate as buses progress through their routes.

*Impact of Schedule Change*

Before the schedule change (Nov 11 \- Dec 13), mean delay was 2.75 minutes (95% CI: \[2.70, 2.81\]) with 66.3% of departures late (delay \> 0 min). Immediately after the change but before holidays (Dec 14-27), mean delay dropped to 1.81 minutes (95% CI: \[1.75, 1.87\]) with 64.3% late, a reduction of 34%. During the holiday period (Dec 28 \- Jan 5), delays decreased further to 1.37 minutes (95% CI: \[1.30, 1.44\]). After the holiday ended, delays increased to 2.17 minutes (95% CI: \[2.12, 2.23\]) but remained 21% lower than pre-change levels

![][image2]Figure 2: Schedule change vs holiday effect analysis. (A) Daily mean delay time series with shaded region indicating the holiday period (Dec 28 \- Jan 5\) and dashed line marking the schedule change (Dec 14 2025). (B) Hourly delay pattern comparing pre change, post-change, and total periods. Post-change delays are lower during daytime hours (6-19h) but higher during night hours.

*Line-Specific Variation*

Figure: Network graph with 2 example lines highlighted 

Delay patterns vary across bus lines. Among city bus lines, Line 34 exhibits the highest mean delay at 17.79 minutes (n=177), followed by Line 32 at 11.90 minutes (n=439) and Line 21 at 9.59 minutes (n=1,106). Night lines also show elevated delays: N96 at 14.01 minutes and N88 at 9.46 minutes. Line 18, despite being cited in public complaints, shows a moderate mean delay of 2.92 minutes but has a high observation count (n=8,863). In contract, Lines 8,, 10, and 3 perform best with mean delays of 1.20, 1.43, and 1.45 minutes respectively.

## Discussion & Conclusion

Vergleich mit T.Ü.B.U.S. \-\> Welche Linien sind laut Studenten am schlimmsten betroffen?  
Tübus: notwendigkeit von mehr bussen vorallem zwischen: **7:30 und 8:15 Uhr (u. a. Linien 5, 13, 14, 17, 18, 19\)** → sehen wir das auch?

The student petition (T.Ü.B.U.S.) specifically highlighted the need for more buses between 7:30-8:15, citing Lines 5, 13, 14, 17, 18, and 19 as problematic. Our data partially contradicts this claim: during morning window (n=6,649), Lines 5, 18, and 19 actually show lower delays than at other times of day (Line 5: 0.94 vs 1.77 min; Line 18: 2.21 vs 2.96 min; Line 19: 0.01 vs 1.72 min). The most delayed lines during 7:30-8:15 are Lines 21 (11.86 min), 16 (8.81 min), and 2 (4.68 min), none of which appear on the petition’s list. This discrepancy may reflect that the petition focused on crowding and frequency rather than delays, or that student heavy routes differ from our observed sample. 

Our analysis reveals that public complaints about bus delays are largely justified. With 65.4% of departures late (delay \> 0 min) and a mean delay of 2.23 minutes, Tübingen’s bus network shows room for improvement. Using a 3-minute threshold for comparison with other cities, 82.2% of departures are on time, comparable to Munich (69.5% at \<= 3 min) and Duisburg (69.3% at \<= 3 min). However, the right-skewed delay distribution means that a substantial minority experience significant delays, particularly during rush hours when the 90th percentile delay reaches 6.9 minutes. Since rush hour buses likely carry more passengers, these delays may affect a disproportionate share of daily riders, potentially explaining why the petition results criticize the bus system despite overall favorable metrics.

The schedule change implemented on December 14, 2025 appears to have had a measurable effect on delays. The 35% reduction in mean delay (from 2.75 to 1.81 min) occurred immediately after the change, before the holiday period began, ruling out reduced holiday traffic as the sole explanation. After holidays ended in January, delays increased but remained 21% lower than pre-change levels (2.17 vs 2.75 min), suggesting the operational adjustments were partially effective. However, we cannot rule out other concurrent factors, and the long-term sustainability of this improvement remains to be seen.

Time-of-day effects dominate the delay patterns. Late night hours show the highest delays (hour 2 at 7.52 min mean), though based on fewer observations (n=1,018). Among daytime hours, the afternoon peak (hour 16\) shows the highest delays at 4.46 minutes mean (n=8,178). Weekend and weekday delays are nearly identical (2.20 vs 2.24 min), suggesting that traffic volume differences between weekdays and weekends do not substantially affect bus punctuality. Weather conditions show that snow has a notable impact (mean 7.50 min vs 2.14 min for dry conditions), though snow accounts for only 2.2% of observations.

Limitations:  
Official data from the city might be biased, cancelled buses might not be shown as delayed and the crowdedness is not measured separately. Due to the structure of the data set, no tracking of accumulated delays of the single buses was possible.

- Weather data not per stop available  
- Seasonal influences (brazil), we only sampled winter data

Our paper has several methodological and data-related limitations that should be considered when interpreting the results. 

Cancelled buses may not appear as delayed in the TRIAS system, potentially underestimating service disruptions. Additionally, the API does not report early arrivals explicitly; buses arriving ahead of schedule are recorded with zero delay, preventing analysis of schedule slack or early departure patterns.

Weather observations were obtained from a single DWD station (Rottenburg-Kiebingen) and applied uniformly across all stops. Local weather variations within Tübingen are not captured. This coarse spatial resolution may weaken observed weather-delay correlations.

Our data collection was focused on a 7 km radius around Tübingen’s center, so coordinates were only retrieved for stops within this area. Stops on routes extending beyond this radius are present in delay data but may lack geographic information, limiting network visualizations. Lines serving Reutlingen, Betzingen, or other outlying areas are incompletely represented in spatial analyses. 

T.Ü.B.U.S emphasized overcrowding as a primary concern, yet the TRIAS API provides no passenger load data. Our analysis addresses punctuality but cannot evaluate capacity utilization or passenger comfort, which may explain discrepancies between our delay findings and subjective rider experiences.
